WEBVTT

00:04.137 --> 00:05.038 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good evening.

00:05.138 --> 00:06.874 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:06.974 --> 00:11.011 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
On the "NewsHour" tonight: President-elect
Donald Trump adds two new names to work for

00:11.111 --> 00:12.613 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
him in the White House.

00:12.713 --> 00:17.084 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Then: another big winner on Election Day,
marijuana.

00:17.184 --> 00:20.320 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
We explore the new legal landscape.

00:20.420 --> 00:21.622 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And it's Friday.

00:21.722 --> 00:24.825 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Mark Shields and David Brooks analyze the
week's news.

00:24.925 --> 00:31.965 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
All that and more on tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

00:32.065 --> 00:34.902 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

00:35.002 --> 00:43.977 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JUDY WOODRUFF: President-elect Donald Trump
has added two more names to his White House

00:44.077 --> 00:45.946 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
staff.

00:46.046 --> 00:50.150 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The announcement came today from Palm Beach,
Florida, where Mr. Trump is spending the holiday.

00:50.250 --> 00:51.418 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Kathleen "K.T."

00:51.518 --> 00:54.988 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
McFarland was appointed deputy national security
adviser.

00:55.088 --> 01:00.294 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
She's worked in several Republican administrationsand as a FOX News analyst.

01:00.394 --> 01:03.063 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
&nbsp;
And Donald McGahn will be White House counsel.

01:03.163 --> 01:05.966 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
He served as the Trump campaign's attorney.

01:06.066 --> 01:09.536 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
Neither appointment is subject to Senate confirmation.

01:09.636 --> 01:15.309 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
In a separate development, Green Party leader
Jill Stein filed a petition formally requesting

01:15.409 --> 01:21.181 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
a presidential vote recount in Wisconsin to
ensure the results were not manipulated.

01:21.281 --> 01:24.418 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
It is expected to begin late next week.

01:24.518 --> 01:29.323 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Similar challenges are also being preparedin Pennsylvania and Michigan.

01:29.423 --> 01:33.994 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
In the day's other news: The death toll from
a massive truck bombing in Southern Iraq rose

01:34.094 --> 01:35.996 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to at least 73.

01:36.096 --> 01:40.400 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
At least 40 of the dead were said to be Shiite
pilgrims from Iran.

01:40.500 --> 01:45.439 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The Islamic State claimed that it carried
out the suicide attack last night at a gas

01:45.539 --> 01:47.274 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
station near the city of Hillah.

01:47.374 --> 01:51.611 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
It is the worst ISIS attack in Iraq since
July.

01:51.712 --> 01:58.085 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
A train collision in Northern Iran has killed
at least 43 people, and injured 100 more.

01:58.185 --> 02:03.890 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
State TV reports that a moving train derailed
and caught fire after striking a parked train

02:03.991 --> 02:05.859 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on a main rail line.

02:05.959 --> 02:11.965 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Injured passengers flooded an area hospitalin zero -- subzero temperatures.

02:12.065 --> 02:17.070 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Firefighters in Israel worked today to contain
the worst of more than a dozen wildfires.

02:17.170 --> 02:23.143 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The largest forced 60,000 people to evacuatearound the city of Haifa.

02:23.243 --> 02:28.081 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Planes dumped retardant today, but it was
too late to save hundreds of homes.

02:28.181 --> 02:32.753 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Meanwhile, police arrested a dozen people,amid allegations of terrorism.

02:32.853 --> 02:35.889 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
BENJAMIN NETANYAHU, Israeli Prime Minister
(through translator): There are elements of

02:35.989 --> 02:41.461 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
terror here, no doubt, elements with great
hostility toward the state of Israel.

02:41.561 --> 02:46.666 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
We cannot tell yet if this is organized, but
we can see a number of cells operating.

02:46.767 --> 02:51.872 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I don't know if there is a connection between
them, and such a connection isn't even necessary.

02:51.972 --> 02:56.209 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
It could be a terror of knives, and it could
be a terror of fires.

02:56.309 --> 03:01.014 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So far, there have been no
reports of deaths or serious injuries.

03:01.114 --> 03:05.652 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The president of Turkey threatened today to
reopen the flow of Middle Eastern and African

03:05.752 --> 03:07.521 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
migrants into Europe.

03:07.621 --> 03:13.226 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Recep Tayyip Erdogan spoke a day after the
European Parliament called for freezing talks

03:13.326 --> 03:15.896 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
to admit Turkey to the European Union.

03:15.996 --> 03:21.134 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
That Parliament vote was aimed at Erdogan's
political and news media crackdown since a

03:21.234 --> 03:23.937 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
failed coup in July.

03:24.037 --> 03:29.342 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
In Bulgaria, violent clashes broke out between
migrants and police last night, leading to

03:29.443 --> 03:31.545 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
some 400 arrests.

03:31.645 --> 03:37.050 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Officials said more than 2,000 asylum-seekers
rioted after being confined to their camp

03:37.150 --> 03:39.286 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
over a health scare.

03:39.386 --> 03:42.689 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Demonstrators threw rocks and set trash on
fire.

03:42.789 --> 03:45.492 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
Police fired tear gas and rubber bullets.

03:45.592 --> 03:49.096 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Bulgaria's prime minister vowed today to punish
those responsible.

03:49.196 --> 03:52.732 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
BOYKO BORISSOV, Bulgarian Prime Minister (through
translator): We have everything filmed, and

03:52.833 --> 03:54.801 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
all these acts of vandalism committed.

03:54.901 --> 03:57.204 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
All migrants who took part will be charged.

03:57.304 --> 04:00.540 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
A small group will be banned and can immediately
be extradited.

04:00.640 --> 04:05.946 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
The others, who all behaved brutally and violated
public order, will be relocated to closed-door

04:06.046 --> 04:07.914 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
refugee camps.

04:08.014 --> 04:12.252 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Meanwhile, in Greece, two migrants,
including a young boy, were killed in a fire

04:12.352 --> 04:14.888 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
at a camp on the island of Lesbos.

04:14.988 --> 04:17.324 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
Police said it was sparked by a gas stove.

04:17.424 --> 04:22.762 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Hurricane Otto weakened to a tropical storm
and headed into the Pacific Ocean after crossing

04:22.863 --> 04:24.397 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Central America.

04:24.498 --> 04:29.002 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The storm battered Nicaragua and Costa Ricaand killed at least nine people.

04:29.102 --> 04:32.606 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
&nbsp;
Otto was an unusually strong late-season hurricane.

04:32.706 --> 04:38.645 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
In some places, as much rain fell in a few
hours as normally falls in a month.

04:38.745 --> 04:43.483 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Back in this country, a federal judge ruled
the man accused of a massacre at a Charleston,

04:43.583 --> 04:47.387 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
South Carolina, church is competent to stand
trial.

04:47.487 --> 04:52.959 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
Dylann Roof allegedly killed nine black churchgoers
in June of 2015.

04:53.059 --> 04:57.564 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
He faces federal counts of hate crimes and
obstruction of religion.

04:57.664 --> 05:02.335 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
He will eventually face a separate trial on
state murder charges.

05:02.435 --> 05:08.441 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Wall Street worked a half-day, but hit more
record closes, as the post-election rally

05:08.542 --> 05:10.110 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
continued.

05:10.210 --> 05:14.314 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The Dow Jones industrial average gained almost69 points to finish at 19152.

05:14.414 --> 05:19.586 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The Nasdaq rose 18 points, and the S&amp;P 500
added eight.

05:19.686 --> 05:21.888 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
It is up 4 percent this month.

05:21.988 --> 05:26.726 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
For the week, all three indexes grew about
1.5 percent.

05:26.826 --> 05:32.299 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And one of television's most beloved moms,
Florence Henderson, has died in Los Angeles

05:32.399 --> 05:34.134 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of heart failure.

05:34.234 --> 05:39.873 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
She gained enduring fame as Carol Brady on
the 1970s sitcom "The Brady Bunch," but she

05:39.973 --> 05:42.309 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
also had success on Broadway.

05:42.409 --> 05:47.781 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Her roles included the female lead in "Oklahoma"
and "The Girl Who Came to Supper."

05:47.881 --> 05:50.217 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
Florence Henderson was 82 years old.

05:50.317 --> 05:56.089 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Still to come on the "NewsHour": a look at
the new legal landscape for marijuana; Shields

05:56.189 --> 06:13.740 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and Brooks on the week's news; and author
Michael Chabon on his latest novel.

06:13.840 --> 06:17.510 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
President-elect Donald Trump continues to
fill positions in his administration over

06:17.611 --> 06:20.480 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
this Thanksgiving holiday weekend.

06:20.580 --> 06:23.450 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
John Yang has more on one with added significance.

06:23.550 --> 06:28.722 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JOHN YANG: To examine the role of the White
House counsel and the challenges Donald McGahn

06:28.822 --> 06:33.426 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
faces tackling president-elect Trump's business
holdings, we're joined by Jack Quinn, who

06:33.526 --> 06:36.529 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
was White House counsel under President Bill
Clinton.

06:36.630 --> 06:37.864 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Jack Quinn, welcome.

06:37.964 --> 06:39.733 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JACK QUINN, Former White House Counsel: Thank
you, John.

06:39.833 --> 06:43.870 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JOHN YANG: When a White House counsel approaches
an issue like figuring out what to do with

06:43.970 --> 06:50.310 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
a president's business holdings, is the client
the president as a individual or the presidency

06:50.410 --> 06:51.311 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as an institution?

06:51.411 --> 06:53.680 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
JACK QUINN: It's definitely the latter.

06:53.780 --> 06:58.318 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
As White House counsel, you represent the
office of the president of United States,

06:58.418 --> 07:01.388 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
not the individual, whether it's Bill Clinton
or Donald Trump.

07:01.488 --> 07:07.193 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JOHN YANG: So, in this case, the counsel may
be looking at having to tell the president

07:07.294 --> 07:12.098 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
as an individual maybe he can't do what he
wants or maybe what he wants to do isn't a

07:12.198 --> 07:13.099 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
good idea?

07:13.199 --> 07:15.068 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
JACK QUINN: That's right.

07:15.168 --> 07:18.872 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And the White House counsel is in the one
who is in a position to invoke executive privilege,

07:18.972 --> 07:20.707 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for example.

07:20.807 --> 07:25.445 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
A White House counsel cannot participate in
a private litigation involving a president

07:25.545 --> 07:32.719 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
in his individual capacity and use that power
to influence the outcome of the litigation.

07:32.819 --> 07:34.521 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
That would be inappropriate.

07:34.621 --> 07:41.528 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And while it's true that the president is
exempt in certain senses from the conflict

07:41.628 --> 07:48.868 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
of interest rules, as are other federal officials,
for good reason, that is not a blank check,

07:48.968 --> 07:50.203 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
so to speak.

07:50.303 --> 07:55.175 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
There are other governors on the conduct of
the presidency.

07:55.275 --> 08:02.816 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The president may not accept emoluments, or,
in other words, economic benefits, from foreign

08:02.916 --> 08:09.022 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
powers, still has to file disclosure of his
financial information, and, most importantly,

08:09.122 --> 08:14.861 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
ultimately, is governed by the impeachment
provisions, which enable the Congress to remove

08:14.961 --> 08:21.034 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
a president if he commits high crimes or misdemeanors,
which is generally understood to mean an abuse

08:21.134 --> 08:22.836 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of power.

08:22.936 --> 08:28.341 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JOHN YANG: So, is the standard -- the standard
is more than just the letter of the law?

08:28.441 --> 08:33.179 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Is there something broader that a counsel
looks at when advising the president on something

08:33.279 --> 08:35.181 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
like the business holdings?

08:35.281 --> 08:37.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JACK QUINN: Sure.

08:37.150 --> 08:42.655 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Well, the White House counsel and others need
to look not just at the letter of the law,

08:42.756 --> 08:48.762 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
but also at the power of the Congress, which
is equally broad, to invoke the impeachment

08:48.862 --> 08:51.564 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
provisions, for example, if a president does
abuse the power.

08:51.664 --> 08:57.036 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Remember, the conflict of interest provision
simply says you can't participate in a decision

08:57.137 --> 09:00.373 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
that would affect you or a member of your
family financially.

09:00.473 --> 09:06.679 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
It doesn't mean that you can use the power
of government to influence this -- to create

09:06.780 --> 09:09.516 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
decisions that would benefit you.

09:09.616 --> 09:13.019 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
We're really in unchartered territory when
it comes to that.

09:13.119 --> 09:19.225 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
That's not to presume that anything of this
kind will take place, but this is, as I say,

09:19.325 --> 09:20.460 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
not a blank check.

09:20.560 --> 09:22.295 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I think it's an appropriate metaphor in this
case.

09:22.395 --> 09:26.933 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JOHN YANG: So, in addition to sort of the
ethics questions that the counsel looks at,

09:27.033 --> 09:33.139 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
what other areas in sort of representing the
institutional interests of the presidency,

09:33.239 --> 09:35.775 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
what other areas is the White House counsel
looking at?

09:35.875 --> 09:42.115 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JACK QUINN: Well, look, ultimately what one
wants to do is ensure that the American people

09:42.215 --> 09:47.320 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
have faith in their government, in their president,
and everyone who works for their president.

09:47.420 --> 09:54.894 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
So it is awfully important that the White
House counsel do everything possible to make

09:54.994 --> 10:02.368 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
sure that the appearance of conflict, the
appearance of self-dealing is avoided.

10:02.469 --> 10:04.237 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
That's critically important.

10:04.337 --> 10:08.007 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
As I say, other officials, and the White House
counsel and the president himself need to

10:08.107 --> 10:10.944 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
provide that assurance to the American people
as well.

10:11.044 --> 10:15.048 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JOHN YANG: You have been -- before you held
the office, you had been counsel to the vice

10:15.148 --> 10:17.050 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
president, Al Gore at the time.

10:17.150 --> 10:20.253 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
You had experience on the Hill, political
campaigns.

10:20.353 --> 10:24.824 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Is there anything that really can prepare
anyone for becoming White House counsel?

10:24.924 --> 10:27.260 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
JACK QUINN: No.

10:27.360 --> 10:33.299 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
There are so many things that come up in a
job like that that -- you know, when I walked

10:33.399 --> 10:38.371 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
into the office the first time, I thought
there would be volumes on the shelves of prior

10:38.471 --> 10:39.372 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
decisions.

10:39.472 --> 10:41.207 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's not like that at all.

10:41.307 --> 10:44.878 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
You do have the Office of Legal Counsel over
at the Justice Department that is helpful,

10:44.978 --> 10:50.483 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and you have a large staff of lawyers who
help you do the research necessary to make

10:50.583 --> 10:52.285 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
good decisions.

10:52.385 --> 10:57.557 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
But decisions come up all the time that are
novel, that have never come up before.

10:57.657 --> 11:04.597 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
And, you know, you have to exercise good judgment,
again, remembering all of the time that you're

11:04.697 --> 11:09.335 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
in a position of sacred trust, as are all
the other people around you, and ultimately

11:09.435 --> 11:14.274 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
you have got to make a judgment that is in
the interest of the American people and the

11:14.374 --> 11:15.375 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
conduct of good government.

11:15.475 --> 11:17.110 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
JOHN YANG: And there is no manual, no handbook.

11:17.210 --> 11:18.411 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
JACK QUINN: There is not.

11:18.511 --> 11:22.415 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JOHN YANG: Jack Quinn, thanks so much for
joining us.

11:22.515 --> 11:29.656 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JACK QUINN: You're so welcome.

11:29.756 --> 11:36.429 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Lost amid November's election
results was the large number of states that

11:36.529 --> 11:41.868 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
legalized the use of marijuana for either
recreational or medical purposes.

11:41.968 --> 11:48.107 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The results spell one of the biggest shifts
in U.S. drug policy in decades, but significant

11:48.207 --> 11:49.776 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
questions remain.

11:49.876 --> 11:51.578 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
William Brangham has the story.

11:51.678 --> 11:55.381 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Legalizing marijuana was
on the ballot in nine different states in

11:55.481 --> 11:56.382 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
this past election.

11:56.482 --> 11:59.118 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
And except in Arizona, they all passed.

11:59.218 --> 12:05.058 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Four states, Montana, North Dakota, Arkansas,
and Florida, voted to legalize use of marijuana

12:05.158 --> 12:07.093 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
for certain medical conditions.

12:07.193 --> 12:13.366 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
And four other states, Maine, Nevada, Massachusetts,
and California, legalized marijuana for anyone

12:13.466 --> 12:15.935 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
21 years and over.

12:16.035 --> 12:19.772 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
This means that millions more people will
be able to purchase marijuana in sanctioned

12:19.872 --> 12:24.711 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
state-approved shops, but, according to federal
law, the drug is still illegal, and the Trump

12:24.811 --> 12:28.781 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
administration could choose on day one tostart enforcing that law.

12:28.881 --> 12:32.752 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
To help us understand the complexity of all
this, I'm joined now by Taylor West, who is

12:32.852 --> 12:37.624 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
the deputy director of the National Cannabis
Industry Association, and John Hudak, who

12:37.724 --> 12:41.060 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
studies drug policy, among other things, atthe Brookings Institution.

12:41.160 --> 12:42.762 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
&nbsp;
Welcome to you both.

12:42.862 --> 12:45.431 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
Taylor, I would like to start with you first.

12:45.531 --> 12:50.003 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Election Day had to be an enormous day for
your industry.

12:50.103 --> 12:52.672 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Do you think of this as a tipping point going
forward?

12:52.772 --> 12:54.741 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
TAYLOR WEST, Deputy Director, National Cannabis
Industry Association: Absolutely.

12:54.841 --> 12:59.412 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
This was a watershed day for the industry
of cannabis, but also for cannabis policy

12:59.512 --> 13:01.280 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the U.S.

13:01.381 --> 13:06.919 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
We saw, as you said, eight states vote for
some form of legal, regulated marijuana program.

13:07.020 --> 13:12.992 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
We now have 20 percent of the country living
in a state that has access to legal marijuana,

13:13.092 --> 13:17.764 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and more than 60 percent of the country living
in a state that has legal access to medical

13:17.864 --> 13:19.666 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
marijuana.

13:19.766 --> 13:22.835 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
This is in line with what we have seen from
public opinion polls, so it really does reflect

13:22.935 --> 13:26.139 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
the direction that the country is moving on
these issues.

13:26.239 --> 13:28.441 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: John Hudak, tipping point?

13:28.541 --> 13:32.211 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Do you think this is just the inevitable roll
of this sort of policy going out across the

13:32.311 --> 13:34.080 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
country?

13:34.180 --> 13:36.449 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JOHN HUDAK, Brookings Institution: This was
absolutely the biggest day of the marijuana

13:36.549 --> 13:38.551 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
reform hands-down.

13:38.651 --> 13:41.120 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
In terms of it being a tipping point, it's
a bit hard to tell.

13:41.220 --> 13:46.092 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I think, in the short term, we're not going
to see much movement at the federal level.

13:46.192 --> 13:48.761 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
What happened in this election was big for
marijuana.

13:48.861 --> 13:53.132 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
But what also happened was the status quo
in Congress, the same leadership in Congress,

13:53.232 --> 13:55.501 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
who, frankly, is opposed to reform.

13:55.601 --> 14:01.908 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
But what this change in the landscape of marijuana
policy can do is to start to embolden the

14:02.008 --> 14:07.013 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
industry, to start to get the industry having
a stronger voice, a more powerful voice, and

14:07.113 --> 14:12.118 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
a more powerful economic voice to eventually
move policy in the right direction toward

14:12.218 --> 14:14.787 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
their interests in reform.

14:14.887 --> 14:18.124 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: John, staying with you,
I mean, as I mentioned in the introduction,

14:18.224 --> 14:21.594 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
this is still illegal as far as the federal
government is concerned.

14:21.694 --> 14:25.998 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And the Obama administration put out a memo
basically saying to states, if you guys run

14:26.099 --> 14:28.935 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
a tight ship, we're not going to interfere
in what you're doing.

14:29.035 --> 14:34.207 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Now, the Trump administration could come andundo that memo in an instant.

14:34.307 --> 14:36.042 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
&nbsp;
Do you think that we're going to see that?

14:36.142 --> 14:39.879 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
What do you imagine when Trump takes over
that that administration is going to do with

14:39.979 --> 14:41.748 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
regards to marijuana?

14:41.848 --> 14:46.586 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JOHN HUDAK: President-elect Trump has voiced
some interest in keeping the status quo when

14:46.686 --> 14:48.454 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
it comes to medical marijuana.

14:48.554 --> 14:52.024 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
His words around recreational marijuana have
been less firm.

14:52.125 --> 14:57.430 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
So, I think, right now, we don't know for
sure what Donald Trump will do on marijuana.

14:57.530 --> 15:00.933 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I think that's true on a lot of policy areas,but it's true with marijuana.

15:01.033 --> 15:04.804 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I think his attorney general pick is one that
worries industry.

15:04.904 --> 15:05.972 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
He's a vowed prohibitionist.

15:06.072 --> 15:07.073 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: This is Jeff Sessions.

15:07.173 --> 15:09.008 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
JOHN HUDAK: Jeff Sessions from Alabama.

15:09.108 --> 15:14.280 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
He's someone who has injected subjective judgment
onto not just marijuana, but the marijuana

15:14.380 --> 15:16.149 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
user.

15:16.249 --> 15:20.086 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
So, I think however much leash that Donald
Trump gives his attorney general will determine

15:20.186 --> 15:25.925 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
whether the Obama doctrine on marijuana holds
the day or whether we see a real transformation

15:26.025 --> 15:27.860 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
back to years past.

15:27.960 --> 15:32.064 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Taylor, as John points out,
Jeff Sessions, who likely will be the attorney

15:32.165 --> 15:36.936 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
general, has been very clear that he doesn't
like what states all over the country are

15:37.036 --> 15:39.205 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
doing with regards to recreational marijuana.

15:39.305 --> 15:45.745 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Does your industry worry that, come January,
you might all of a sudden face federal enforcement?

15:45.845 --> 15:50.082 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
TAYLOR WEST: It is certainly something that
we're keeping an eye on.

15:50.183 --> 15:55.454 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The fact is that, during the campaign, as
John mentioned, president-elect Trump said

15:55.555 --> 16:01.394 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
on multiple occasions that he really did see
this as a state issue, and that programs in

16:01.494 --> 16:06.766 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
the states that have been chosen by the voters
should be allowed to move forward.

16:06.866 --> 16:12.939 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Certainly, Senator Sessions has expressed
his personal opinion on issues around marijuana,

16:13.039 --> 16:18.144 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
but the reality is that Senator Sessions has
also on many occasions been a strong advocate

16:18.244 --> 16:22.448 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
of state sovereignty and the concept of federalism.

16:22.548 --> 16:29.522 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
So I think there really is a nexus of agreement
there on the idea that a program chosen by

16:29.622 --> 16:34.560 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
the voters of the state working in the way
that it's meant to ought to be respected.

16:34.660 --> 16:39.365 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
Now, as John said, there's still some uncertainty
about exactly which direction any of these

16:39.465 --> 16:43.536 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
policies will go, but we do see that sort
of path forward.

16:43.636 --> 16:45.771 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: John, let's take Taylor's
point.

16:45.872 --> 16:48.474 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Let's assume that the federal government doesn't
interfere.

16:48.574 --> 16:53.112 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Aren't we still going to see conflict, though,
between federal law and state law?

16:53.212 --> 16:54.680 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
There are still other problems.

16:54.780 --> 16:58.551 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
I mean, banks, for instance, can't take marijuana
money.

16:58.651 --> 17:00.386 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
And that causes a huge problem for the industry.

17:00.486 --> 17:01.754 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
Those things have got to get worked out eventually.

17:01.854 --> 17:03.589 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

17:03.689 --> 17:05.958 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JOHN HUDAK: The reforms that have happened
during the Obama administration have allowed

17:06.058 --> 17:11.330 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
the industry to really get up and running
and have cover, feel safe that what they are

17:11.430 --> 17:14.700 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
going to do will be protected from federal
intervention.

17:14.800 --> 17:20.940 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
But, at the same time, the Cole memos, which
have really taken this enforcement discretion

17:21.040 --> 17:28.547 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to a formal stance from the Obama administration
policy, does create these unintended consequences

17:28.648 --> 17:34.020 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
around taxes, around banking, around interstate
access, around a variety of issues that can

17:34.120 --> 17:36.622 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
be very challenging for the industry.

17:36.722 --> 17:40.092 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
Those are going to need to be addressed eventually.

17:40.192 --> 17:42.128 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
We just don't know when that will happen.

17:42.228 --> 17:47.733 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Taylor, we have seen already
Colorado and Washington have had a period

17:47.833 --> 17:52.838 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
of time where their legalization infrastructure
has been built, their licensing, their taxing,

17:52.939 --> 17:54.640 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
their selling.

17:54.740 --> 17:59.612 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Do those states' experience over the last
years or so give us any sense of how this

17:59.712 --> 18:02.381 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
is going to go forward for other states thatare just trying this out?

18:02.481 --> 18:06.385 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
TAYLOR WEST: Well, I think there are a couple
important lessons to take from what we have

18:06.485 --> 18:09.221 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
seen in places like Colorado and Washington.

18:09.322 --> 18:15.061 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The biggest one is that, by and large, this
works, that these programs have been implemented

18:15.161 --> 18:16.595 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
successfully.

18:16.696 --> 18:19.532 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
We haven't seen the major issues that opponents
were concerned about.

18:19.632 --> 18:21.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The sky hasn't fallen.

18:21.600 --> 18:27.106 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And then a secondary lesson to that is that,
when there have been problems that have arisen,

18:27.206 --> 18:30.977 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
the legislature and regulators have been able
to address them.

18:31.077 --> 18:34.380 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
That's something that you don't get in an
unregulated system.

18:34.480 --> 18:39.552 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And I think that's an important thing for
states that are now embarking on these programs

18:39.652 --> 18:44.724 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
to realize, that they have given themselves
the power to shape this industry in their

18:44.824 --> 18:46.659 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
states as it grows.

18:46.759 --> 18:52.531 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
So, those are things that I think are important,
both from the state implementation standpoint

18:52.631 --> 18:58.070 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and something that's important for the federalleaders to remember as well.

18:58.170 --> 19:01.974 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Turning back the clock on this doesn't just
end regulated sales.

19:02.074 --> 19:06.879 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
It really sends them back into a criminal
market that we have very little control over.

19:06.979 --> 19:10.116 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: John, last question for
you.

19:10.216 --> 19:11.951 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
What happens on the legal front?

19:12.051 --> 19:17.123 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
If people are -- now have a criminal record
because of marijuana sales or possession,

19:17.223 --> 19:22.495 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
or are in prison for marijuana sales or possession,
do these legalization schemes have any say

19:22.595 --> 19:23.829 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in that?

19:23.929 --> 19:26.132 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Does anyone get their record expunged or looked
at again?

19:26.232 --> 19:31.170 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JOHN HUDAK: Some of the legalization efforts
have put these issues at the forefront.

19:31.270 --> 19:37.176 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
California, for instance, built into its initiative
the ability of individuals who were arrested

19:37.276 --> 19:43.382 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and charged with low-level marijuana offenses,
effectively what were formerly offenses that

19:43.482 --> 19:48.521 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
would now be considered legal in California,
to go to court and ask for their record to

19:48.621 --> 19:49.588 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be expunged.

19:49.688 --> 19:51.924 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
Now, those are very specific circumstances.

19:52.024 --> 19:56.662 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
They obviously couldn't be done in conjunction
with violent crimes or larger crimes.

19:56.762 --> 20:03.436 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
But these are issues that affect particularly
communities of color and create barriers to

20:03.536 --> 20:08.841 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
economic opportunity, barriers to educational
opportunity, and have really long-term effects

20:08.941 --> 20:12.812 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
on an individual who faces criminal justice
through this process.

20:12.912 --> 20:18.017 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And so some states have really spearheaded
the ability to do this, but as more states

20:18.117 --> 20:23.489 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
have come online, that conversation has broadened
and these criminal justice reform issues have

20:23.589 --> 20:28.761 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
become not dominant, but at least pushed to
the front of the line in terms of issues that

20:28.861 --> 20:29.995 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
are talked about.

20:30.096 --> 20:31.564 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And I think that's a very important part of
this.

20:31.664 --> 20:33.099 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right.

20:33.199 --> 20:37.503 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
John Hudak and Taylor West, thank you bothvery much for being here.

20:37.603 --> 20:42.741 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
&nbsp;
JOHN HUDAK: Thank you.

20:42.842 --> 20:47.980 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
TAYLOR WEST: Thank you.

