21:28.020 --> 21:29.755 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
What are we learning from this?

21:29.855 --> 21:32.992 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
What are we -- what do you now understand
about him that we didn't understand before?

21:33.092 --> 21:34.827 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Not much.

21:34.927 --> 21:40.499 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I mean, I would say that there's been the
small Donald, the petty, vindictive Donald,

21:40.599 --> 21:44.570 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
who can be rather mean-spirited, as he was
on display at The New York Times editorial

21:44.670 --> 21:51.043 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
board meeting, where he gratuitously took
out after Kelly Ayotte, the former Republican

21:51.143 --> 21:55.981 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
-- senior Republican senator in New Hampshire,
who had -- after the "Access Hollywood" tape

21:56.081 --> 21:59.718 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
had refused to support Donald Trump and said
she couldn't get a job.

21:59.818 --> 22:06.892 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And then we see the little bit larger Donald
in hiring Nikki Haley, who had, in fact, backed

22:06.992 --> 22:14.400 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
both Marco Rubio and Ted Cruz and in the national
address, in response -- the official Republican

22:14.500 --> 22:18.871 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
response to the president's State of the Union,
had warned the party against following the

22:18.971 --> 22:25.511 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
siren call of those -- it was a direct allusionto Donald Trump at the time.

22:25.611 --> 22:29.715 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
&nbsp;
So he was larger in spirit in choosing her.

22:29.815 --> 22:37.189 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
And she certainly is a person who has demonstrated
leadership and character under stress at the

22:37.289 --> 22:41.694 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
time of the massacre, the racial massacre
at the Mother Emanuel Church in Charleston

22:41.794 --> 22:47.800 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and leading in lowering the Confederate Battle
Flag over the state -- on the state capitol

22:47.900 --> 22:48.801 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
grounds.

22:48.901 --> 22:49.802 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David?

22:49.902 --> 22:50.803 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

22:50.903 --> 22:51.804 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Excuse me.

22:51.904 --> 22:52.805 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I didn't mean to interrupt.

22:52.905 --> 22:54.807 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Sure.

22:54.907 --> 22:56.308 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What are you learning about
Donald Trump from these appointments or announcements?

22:56.408 --> 22:58.344 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
DAVID BROOKS: Well, I guess it's -- yes, of
some comfort, I guess.

22:58.444 --> 23:02.815 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Sometimes, the campaign seemed to be, as Mark
said, vindictive, but sort of a depraved three-ring

23:02.915 --> 23:03.849 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
circus.

23:03.949 --> 23:05.951 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
The transition period has not been that.

23:06.051 --> 23:11.023 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
He's nominated people like DeVos or Haley
who are competent people, who are more or

23:11.123 --> 23:14.126 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
less professional, experienced people.

23:14.226 --> 23:17.463 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
They may not be, on substantive ground, all
of our cup of tea.

23:17.563 --> 23:22.401 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
They are very consistent with the way he campaigned,
a nationalist campaign on education policy,

23:22.501 --> 23:25.104 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
a campaign that is enthusiastic about school
choice.

23:25.204 --> 23:30.376 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
But they are more or less the sort of professionalversion of Trump's ideology.

23:30.476 --> 23:36.282 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And I do think there is just this animating
spirit here to create a sort of nationalist,

23:36.382 --> 23:41.720 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
populist conservatism that will in some ways
stretch the Republican Party and in some ways

23:41.820 --> 23:43.589 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
offend a lot of conservatives.

23:43.689 --> 23:46.925 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
But I think there is an animating vision here
to try to create a movement that will last

23:47.026 --> 23:51.797 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
post-Trump, a populist movement that may even
try to span some of the dividing lines that

23:51.897 --> 23:56.735 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
have existed so far through large economic
policies, through infrastructure policies,

23:56.835 --> 24:01.807 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
through a tough anti-terror policy that nonetheless
keeps American troops out of war.

24:01.907 --> 24:05.411 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
There's an animating vision here, and it's
being executed, at least in the appointments

24:05.511 --> 24:08.347 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
so far, in some intellectually coherent way.

24:08.447 --> 24:10.215 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, a movement in the making
maybe?

24:10.316 --> 24:15.087 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MARK SHIELDS: A movement in the making -- I
guess I don't share David's enthusiasm about

24:15.187 --> 24:16.722 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Betsy DeVos.

24:16.822 --> 24:21.727 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I mean, 90 percent of American schoolchildrenare in public schools, Judy.

24:21.827 --> 24:29.268 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And the emphasis on private schools and charter
schools and parochial schools is not unimportant.

24:29.368 --> 24:31.370 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
I don't mean that, but we're at 90 percent.

24:31.470 --> 24:34.473 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
We're heading to 91 percent will be in public
schools.

24:34.573 --> 24:37.710 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I'm not sure Betsy DeVos has ever spent a
day in a public school.

24:37.810 --> 24:40.813 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And I don't -- I'm pretty sure Donald Trump
hasn't.

24:40.913 --> 24:49.254 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
So, I do look upon the secretary of education's
primary responsibility as the quality of education

24:49.355 --> 24:53.859 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
that -- and improving the education that every
child in American public schools receives.

24:53.959 --> 24:55.294 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What about that, David?

24:55.394 --> 24:56.295 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What about Betsy...

24:56.395 --> 24:57.296 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes.

24:57.396 --> 24:58.297 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Go ahead, yes.

24:58.397 --> 24:59.465 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes.

24:59.565 --> 25:00.933 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
First of all, charter schools are public schools.

25:01.033 --> 25:02.501 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
They're paid for publicly and they're part
of the public system.

25:02.601 --> 25:04.670 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
They just have a more independent structure.

25:04.770 --> 25:06.972 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And so I guess I would say, we need a reform
movement.

25:07.072 --> 25:10.642 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
We have seen, I think, in the charter school
movement started out, whatever it was, 10

25:10.743 --> 25:13.946 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
or 15 years ago -- it's increasingly gotten
better.

25:14.046 --> 25:15.814 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Charter schools are figuring out how to do
this.

25:15.914 --> 25:19.918 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The charter schools that are most effective
are scaling the most quickly, and so there's

25:20.018 --> 25:22.154 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
got to be a continued move for reform.

25:22.254 --> 25:25.824 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
At the same time, the teachers unions are
pushing at that reform, has had some political

25:25.924 --> 25:27.659 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
successes.

25:27.760 --> 25:32.064 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And so I think charter schools, choice, and
frankly school standards need a champion.

25:32.164 --> 25:34.133 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
And DeVos has been a good pretty champion.

25:34.233 --> 25:36.101 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
Now, I don't -- she's not without fault.

25:36.201 --> 25:37.970 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
You have got to have two things in education
reform.

25:38.070 --> 25:40.839 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
You have got to have some flexibility, so
people can figure out what to do.

25:40.939 --> 25:45.444 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
But you also have to have accountable, basically
what the Common Core standards were, some

25:45.544 --> 25:48.647 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
sort of set of national standards, so we can
measure.

25:48.747 --> 25:50.582 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
It's hard for parents just to measure schools.

25:50.682 --> 25:53.519 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
DeVos has been really good at the flexibility.

25:53.619 --> 25:55.721 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
She's not been enthusiastic about the accountability.

25:55.821 --> 25:58.257 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
So, she's a complete -- an incomplete operator.

25:58.357 --> 26:00.025 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
But I do think -- I have met her a few times.

26:00.125 --> 26:04.263 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
She's a normal person, a sophisticated person,
in some ways a self-effacing person.

26:04.363 --> 26:09.435 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And she has been at least a champion of reform,
if maybe too much emphasizing choice, not

26:09.535 --> 26:11.236 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
enough, in my view, emphasizing charters.

26:11.336 --> 26:12.237 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You want to come...

26:12.337 --> 26:13.238 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

26:13.338 --> 26:14.973 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes.

26:15.073 --> 26:19.645 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I mean, I just -- I applaud David's interest
in, enthusiasm for charter schools.

26:19.745 --> 26:25.184 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
It's a very mixed record, and particularly
in Detroit, where that's -- the emphasis has

26:25.284 --> 26:26.652 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
been.

26:26.752 --> 26:27.853 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's less than mixed.

26:27.953 --> 26:30.889 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's really discouraging.

26:30.989 --> 26:37.529 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And in the final analysis, American public
education -- American education will be determined

26:37.629 --> 26:42.768 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
by the quality of American public education,
and that's public schools that are available.

26:42.868 --> 26:49.842 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
The charter school is a possibility, an alternative
in certain circumstances, but not in most,

26:49.942 --> 26:54.980 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and not in most places, and not -- most parents
don't have either the time, the inclination

26:55.080 --> 27:00.486 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
or the aptitude to sit and go through sifting
what school and what is available and what

27:00.586 --> 27:02.488 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the options are.

27:02.588 --> 27:06.124 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
They are dependent upon the quality of theirneighborhood and local schools.

27:06.225 --> 27:07.426 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
&nbsp;
JUDY WOODRUFF: David, I want to...

27:07.526 --> 27:08.427 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
DAVID BROOKS: If I could just make...

27:08.527 --> 27:09.595 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Go ahead, yes.

27:09.695 --> 27:10.429 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
DAVID BROOKS: ... one more point on that quickly.

27:10.529 --> 27:12.431 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: OK.

27:12.531 --> 27:14.433 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
DAVID BROOKS: Just, as I have traveled around
from school to school, whether it's project-based

27:14.533 --> 27:16.869 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
learning or an outward bound curriculum, it's
very hard to tell the difference between charters

27:16.969 --> 27:18.203 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and public anymore.

27:18.303 --> 27:20.138 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There's no fine line.

27:20.239 --> 27:22.841 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
They're often adopting very similar programs,
maybe with a different administrative structure.

27:22.941 --> 27:26.345 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
But what I'm saying is, you're seeing reform
throughout the movement, in the so-called

27:26.445 --> 27:29.481 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
charters, in the so-called publics, if we're
going to call them that.

27:29.581 --> 27:32.651 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
And that reform dynamism has to be kept going.

27:32.751 --> 27:37.489 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David, I also want to bring
up with both of you the questions I think

27:37.589 --> 27:42.327 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
that came up day after day this last week
about Donald Trump's business connections,

27:42.427 --> 27:48.534 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
his business -- deep business interests and
how that's going to work as president of the

27:48.634 --> 27:50.402 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
United States.

27:50.502 --> 27:53.672 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
It came up in John Yang's conversation just
now with Jack Quinn, the former White House

27:53.772 --> 27:54.773 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
counsel.

27:54.873 --> 27:56.241 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
How do you see that developing?

27:56.341 --> 27:58.010 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Do you see it as a problem?

27:58.110 --> 28:00.245 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Do you see it as something that Trump is going
to be able to handle?

28:00.345 --> 28:02.047 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What do you see?

28:02.147 --> 28:06.184 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes, I would invite viewers
to go back and read a book by a guy named

28:06.285 --> 28:10.255 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
George Washington Plunkitt of Tammany Hall,
who had a concept called honest graft, where

28:10.355 --> 28:13.592 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
his own public -- private interest corresponded
to public interest.

28:13.692 --> 28:17.162 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
That's what Trumps seems to be advocating,
merging the two.

28:17.262 --> 28:19.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's just bad news.

28:19.131 --> 28:23.201 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And I hope the new presumed White House counsel
will just say, this is not going to work.

28:23.302 --> 28:25.437 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
You have got to have a bright line between
these two things.

28:25.537 --> 28:27.940 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
We're no longer living in Tammany Hall America.

28:28.040 --> 28:31.877 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And it will just lead to scandal after scandal
that will end up hurting your own administration.

28:31.977 --> 28:33.178 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark?

28:33.278 --> 28:34.613 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MARK SHIELDS: I think David is absolutely
right, Judy.

28:34.713 --> 28:36.515 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I think it's very serious.

28:36.615 --> 28:42.387 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I mean, when the -- you have got 70 days between
the election and taking office, an enormous

28:42.487 --> 28:44.256 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
responsibility.

28:44.356 --> 28:49.661 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And when you spend that time actually meeting
with Indian business investors for a Trump

28:49.761 --> 28:57.402 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
apartment complex in Mumbai, when you meet
with Nigel Farage and raise the question of

28:57.502 --> 29:02.007 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
eliminating the wind farm because it would
hurt the view at Donald Trump's golf course

29:02.107 --> 29:07.512 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
in Scotland and urges a change in policy,
I mean, this is the man who doesn't understand

29:07.613 --> 29:11.083 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
the difference between public policy, publictrust and private interest.

29:11.183 --> 29:19.691 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
When you see Ivanka Trump hawking the $10,000
bracelet that she wore on the "60 Minutes"

29:19.791 --> 29:25.931 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
broadcast from her jewelry -- presidential
trust is something, Judy, that's perishable

29:26.031 --> 29:27.799 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and it's precious.

29:27.899 --> 29:31.770 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And once a president loses it, it's not a
question of whether it's conflict of interests

29:31.870 --> 29:34.172 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
laws or there aren't conflict of interests
laws.

29:34.272 --> 29:38.577 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
The president has to have the trust, earn
the trust, maintain the trust of people in

29:38.677 --> 29:40.512 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
order to lead.

29:40.612 --> 29:44.149 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And there's nothing that will lose it quicker
than a sense that he's in it for a quick buck.

29:44.249 --> 29:46.184 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David, do you want to add anything
on that?

29:46.284 --> 29:52.624 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
Because I do want to move on to what is apparently
-- what seems to be a split inside Trump world

29:52.724 --> 29:55.327 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
over who is going to be secretary of state.

29:55.427 --> 30:00.999 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
We saw Kellyanne Conway, who has been sort
of the face of the Trump transition, tweeting

30:01.099 --> 30:07.572 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
openly just yesterday that they're picking
up a lot of criticism about the fact that

30:07.673 --> 30:10.575 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
he's considering Mitt Romney.

30:10.676 --> 30:18.784 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
What does this tell us about folks inside
Trump world who may be dismayed at where Donald

30:18.884 --> 30:20.652 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Trump is headed?

30:20.752 --> 30:23.121 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
DAVID BROOKS: I'm looking forward to the live
tweets of the Oval Office meetings in the

30:23.221 --> 30:24.122 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Trump administration.

30:24.222 --> 30:25.924 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

30:26.024 --> 30:28.293 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
DAVID BROOKS: There's certainly a lot of chaos
and openness that they're saying so far.

30:28.393 --> 30:32.497 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I think Trump is sort of -- from what we can
see from his comments, sort of attracted to

30:32.597 --> 30:34.099 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the idea of a Romney.

30:34.199 --> 30:37.035 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
He looks the part, as Trump -- looks are veryimportant to Donald Trump.

30:37.135 --> 30:40.505 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And so -- but I do think there is some sign
of respectability.

30:40.605 --> 30:43.341 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Personally, I think Mitt Romney would be agreat secretary of state.

30:43.442 --> 30:44.576 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
&nbsp;
He knows a lot.

30:44.676 --> 30:46.378 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
He's a very professional -- a consummate professional.

30:46.478 --> 30:49.347 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Frankly, if I were Donald Trump, I would be
a little suspicious.

30:49.448 --> 30:54.619 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
It's very easy to imagine he's got his America
first crew in the National Security Council.

30:54.720 --> 30:56.455 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
Mitt Romney's a more internationalist.

30:56.555 --> 30:59.658 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
It's easy to see him setting up a foreign
policy establishment over there in the State

30:59.758 --> 31:03.128 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Department that would be a rival to the White
House, and maybe that's a good thing.

31:03.228 --> 31:07.099 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
But, if I were Donald Trump, it's not necessarily
what I would want in my foreign policy apparatus.

31:07.199 --> 31:08.533 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What do you think of the split?

31:08.633 --> 31:11.870 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MARK SHIELDS: Now that David has sunk Mitt
Romney's chances...

31:11.970 --> 31:12.871 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

31:12.971 --> 31:14.339 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

31:14.439 --> 31:16.108 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MARK SHIELDS: ... separate entity over at
the State Department.

31:16.208 --> 31:17.542 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
To me, it's fascinating.

31:17.642 --> 31:19.578 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's a choice.

31:19.678 --> 31:20.979 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Trump loves loyalty.

31:21.079 --> 31:23.381 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
He prizes loyalty, who was with him.

31:23.482 --> 31:25.317 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Rudy was with him.

31:25.417 --> 31:33.825 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
Rudy, you will recall, was the moderate Republican
mayor of New York who was for immigration

31:33.925 --> 31:38.630 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
rights, for gun control, for abortion rights,
for gay rights.

31:38.730 --> 31:43.769 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
He abandoned those positions to endorse Donald
Trump after a disastrous run for president

31:43.869 --> 31:48.640 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
and gave a speech at the convention that sounded
like a New York cab driver stuck in traffic

31:48.740 --> 31:49.808 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
at 4:30 in the afternoon.

31:49.908 --> 31:50.809 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

31:50.909 --> 31:52.677 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
MARK SHIELDS: It was a rant.

31:52.778 --> 31:59.951 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
He went on, Judy, to say, if you will recall,
eight years before -- eight years prior to

32:00.051 --> 32:06.057 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Barack Obama coming in, there were no attacks
on the United States, and they all began when

32:06.158 --> 32:11.930 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Obama and Clinton took office, conveniently
forgetting completely the tragedy, the national

32:12.030 --> 32:13.732 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
tragedy of 9/11.

32:13.832 --> 32:21.706 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
So, there are questions and doubts about Rudy
Giuliani and his competence for the job.

32:21.807 --> 32:25.377 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
But there's no question that Newt Gingrich
is out for him.

32:25.477 --> 32:29.281 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
Kellyanne Conway is apparently advocating
and championing for him.

32:29.381 --> 32:30.715 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
So, this is -- this is a split.

32:30.816 --> 32:34.853 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
I agree with David that Mitt Romney does fit
the bill.

32:34.953 --> 32:36.922 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
He looks like a secretary of state.

32:37.022 --> 32:39.424 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
He looks like the chancellor of the exchequer.

32:39.524 --> 32:41.359 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A lot of people said he would
look like a president.

32:41.459 --> 32:42.360 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
MARK SHIELDS: He looks like a president.

32:42.460 --> 32:43.595 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I mean, he really does.

32:43.695 --> 32:44.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He's central casting.

32:44.896 --> 32:48.033 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
You want a leader, Western leader, English-speaking?

32:48.133 --> 32:49.634 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Mitt Romney.

32:49.734 --> 32:51.403 align:left position:62.5%,start line:86.67% size:37.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right, just a quick minute-and-a-half
on the Democrats.

32:51.503 --> 32:53.638 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
We are going to reserve just a moment for
them.

32:53.738 --> 32:59.010 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
David, we're seeing Chuck Schumer, the incoming
Democratic leader in the Senate, saying, we,

32:59.110 --> 33:03.548 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
the Democrats, need to look at ways possiblyto work with Donald Trump.

33:03.648 --> 33:07.319 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And then, on the other hand, we're seeing
Congressman Keith Ellison, who is up for running

33:07.419 --> 33:12.224 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
for head of the Democratic Party, the Democratic
National Committee say, Mark, say, no, we're

33:12.324 --> 33:15.961 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
not going to be working with him, and I don't
want to hear about it.

33:16.061 --> 33:19.564 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
David, are the Democrats making the rightkind of noises right now?

33:19.664 --> 33:21.600 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
&nbsp;
Or do we just wait and see what happens?

33:21.700 --> 33:26.371 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
DAVID BROOKS: I think Schumer is right to
keep the possibility open that Trump is movable

33:26.471 --> 33:29.741 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
on some issues, which is clearly what Obama
believes, and that they can work with him

33:29.841 --> 33:31.877 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
on some issues, like infrastructure or something
like that.

33:31.977 --> 33:35.013 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
So, I think, if they could have a good six
months where they work together, there will

33:35.113 --> 33:37.616 align:left position:87.5%,start line:93.33% size:12.5%
be plenty of time for fighting later on.

33:37.716 --> 33:38.617 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

33:38.717 --> 33:40.685 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
MARK SHIELDS: David is right.

33:40.785 --> 33:45.123 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
And I think the worst thing the Democrats
could do is to follow the playbook that Mitch

33:45.223 --> 33:49.127 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
McConnell and the Republicans adopted in 2009
against Barack Obama.

33:49.227 --> 33:51.329 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
And that's just total, all-out obstructionism.

33:51.429 --> 33:54.466 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
JUDY WOODRUFF: To say on day one or day two...

33:54.566 --> 33:58.470 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes, that's right, the most
important thing is to defeat him for reelection.

33:58.570 --> 34:00.305 align:left position:75%,start line:93.33% size:25%
I think that America has had enough of it.

34:00.405 --> 34:01.473 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It doesn't work.

34:01.573 --> 34:04.175 align:left position:62.5%,start line:93.33% size:37.5%
And it's not the best of the Democratic tradition.

34:04.276 --> 34:12.717 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark Shields, David Brooks,
thank you very much.

34:12.817 --> 34:29.200 align:left position:75%,start line:86.67% size:25%
